value.value: Neuromast that is part of the anterior lateral line. Kimmel et al, 1995. (Also see Anatomical Atlas entry for lateral line by T. Whitfield.)
Cells (completely cleaved), located underneath the superficial blastomeres and internal to the marginal blastomeres. Kimmel et al, 1995.
Anatomical cluster consisting of the paired sublingual dorsal ossification and sublingual ventral ossification.
Sublingual that is the dorsal element paired with the sublingual ventral ossification.
Sublingual that is the ventral element paired with the sublingual dorsal ossification.
Nerve fibers originating from the dorsal anterior lateral line ganglion.  These rami innervate the otic, supraorbital, and infraorbital neuromasts.
Nerve fibers originating from the ventral anterior lateral line ganglion.  These rami innervate the mandibular and opercular neuromasts.
Nerve fibers originating from the middle lateral line ganglion.  These fibers innervate the middle lateral line.
The middle lateral line ganglion develops from a cranial ectodermal placode and contains sensory neurons that innervate the middle lateral line.
Cells (completely cleaved), located at the surface of the blastodisc, above the deep blastomeres. Kimmel et al, 1995.
Simple columnar epithelium that lines the esophagus. Chen et al, 2007.
Bilaterally paired cartilage encasing the semicircular canals of the inner ear.

Bilaterally paired medial bar of cartilage formed at midorbit through medial chondrification from triangles of cartilage that later form the junction of the taeniae marginales anterior, taeniae marginales posterior and the epiphyseal bar.

Cranial cartilage which is bilaterally paired and develops as a dorsal plate-like projection of the anterolateral ethmoid plate, which are oriented perpendicular to the ethmoid plate. It fuses dorsally to the taenia marginalis anterior, and it joins the ethmoid cartilage medially.

Cranial cartilage which is a paired anterodorsal projection of the posterior end of the parachordal cartilage. It lies lateral to the notochord, just anterior to the posterior tip of the otic capsule. The bilaterally paired occipital arch cartilages fuse anterodorsally to the posterior edges of the auditory capsules and meet medially as the tectum synoticum (by 12 dpf).
Cartilage bar (bilaterally paired) that grows anteroventrally from the epiphyseal bar to join the anterolatera1 edge of the ethmoid plate.
Unpaired thin dorsal sheet of cartilage that partially covers the posterior chondrocranium.

Paired thin medially aligned bar of cartilage that extends from the anterior end of the chondrocranium to just anterior to the anterior end of the notochord. The posterior ends of the trabeculae cranii are continuous with the parachordal cartilages, and they enclose the hypophyseal fenestra.
Cartilage formed via medial fusion between bilaterally paired trabecula crani.
Bilaterally paired thin continuous band of cartilage that sagitally encircles the eye.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is median and is the anterior-most cartilage of the ventral hyoid arch.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates dorsally with the hyosymplectic cartilage or the articulation of the hyomandibula and symplectic.

definition.value: It articulates ventrally with the posterior end of the ceratohyal cartilage or the posterior ceratohyal.

value.value: Cartilage bar (bilaterally paired) that is first visible as an anterior extension of the auditory capsule. It grows anteriorly toward the middle of the orbit where it is connected to its mate on the other side by the epiphyseal bar.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that forms the largest skeletal element of the ventral branchial arches.
Ceratobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 2 cartilage or bone.
Ceratobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 3 cartilage or bone.
Ceratobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 4 cartilage or bone.
Ceratobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 1 cartilage or bone.
Ceratobranchial cartilage that is the most posterior, bilaterally paired ventral pharyngeal arch cartilage.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates medially with a median skeletal element and laterally with a ceratobranchial cartilage or bone.

definition.value: The hypobranchial cartilage usually articulates medially with a basibranchial bone or cartilage.

value.value: Hypobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 4 cartilage or bone.
Hypobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 1 cartilage or bone.
Hypobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 2 cartilage or bone.
Hypobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 3 cartilage or bone.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial cartilage or bone.
Epibranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 1 cartilage or bone.
Epibranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 3 cartilage or bone.
Epibranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 2 cartilage or bone.
Epibranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 4 cartilage or bone.
Sublingual cartilage that is the dorsal element paired with the sublingual ventral cartilage.
Paired cartilages that project medially from the medial tips of epibranchials.
Pharyngobranchial cartilage, located medial to the epibranchials and posteriorly adjacent to pharyngobranchial 2 element.
Pharyngobranchial cartilage, located medial to the epibranchials and posteriorly adjacent to pharyngobranchial 1 element.
Pectoral fin cartilage that is part of the embryonic primary pectoral girdle from which the mesocoracoid bone will ossify endochondrally.
Small cartilage that forms at the posterior edge of the basipterygium.

Bilaterally paired small, rodlike cartilages on the ventral surface of the abdomen (present at 7.9 mm). Their posterior tips expand laterally, forming L-shaped cartilages. Medially, a posterior spur of cartilage develops, which will later ossify as the ischiac process (Weitzman 1962).
Small cartilage that forms at the posterior and medial edge of the basipterygium.
Small cartilage with a long posterior process and a shorter lateral one that forms at the posterior edge of the basipterygium, between radial cartilages 1 and 2.
Small cartilage that forms at the posterior and lateral edge of the basipterygium.
